4. LENNox.

[This was a dukedom, but the great officers of state in Scotland had precedence even of dukes‚ and so are first acknowledged.]

James [Stewart], fourth Duke of Lennox, succecded his father, Esm6, in 1624, who again had succeeded his brother Ludovick (second duke) only a few months before. James died in 1655 of a broken beart under the missortunes of the Royal House, with which he was closely allied ; the House of Lennox being collaterally connected with royalty through Matthew‚ Earl of Lennox, father of Darnley and grandfather of James VI.

Williarn Grahame, seventh Earl of Menteith, Earl (for a time) of Strathern, afterwards suddenly, in 1633, deprived of the Strathern title, the holding ofwhich was held to be dangerous to the crown, it being a royal title ; and instead he was created Earl of Airth. He lost also the presidency ofthe Council. The disappearance of the distich from the Delitiac must be connected with the disappearance from court that befel this earl. His fall was owing to his having been alleged to say ‘⁴ he had reddet blood than the king's ”.
